result.execSummary:
The defendant Nolan J. Whitegull was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Stichert.  Defendant plead no contest to Count 1.  Court advised the defendant of the charge and possible penalties he plead to.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  He understands.  Court confirmed the 2 prior OWI offenses.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis for the charge.  Court finds that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights and entered her plea.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty as plead to.   Defense stipulated to a factual basis for the charge.  Court finds that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights and entered his plea.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty as plead to.  Joint recommendation for court costs only.  Defendant elected to exercise his right to allocution.  Court ordered court costs only.   Pay @ $50/mo., starting 10/15.    Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.

This bond applies to all 15CF64, 14CT40 and 15CM2:  Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on the highways until properly reinstated in the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.  As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.  Until further order of the court, you shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, except through your attorney, with any of the following individuals and/or businesses: Harriet H.

Defendant appeared with counsel Damon Stichert.  ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Attorney Stichert states he is appearing specially on 15CM2 and 14CT40.  Judge granted release of attorney on 15CM2 and 14CT40.  Carly Sebion, SPD was present in the courtroom.  Their office will need a copy of the Order to Release Attorney of Record before they can appoint attorney Stichert to the other cases.  Defense will waive time limits for the prelim and also waives reading of the complaint and enters a not guilty plea.  Judge reviews the rights to a preliminary hearing within the time limits with the defendant.  Finds the defendant knowingly and intelligently waives the time limits for a prelim.  Judge also reviewed charges and penalties on 14CT40 and 15CM2 with defendant.  All cases set for pretrial on 7-1-15 and status on 7-20-15 at 3:00.  Attorney Stichert requests the $3500 cash bond be reduced.  Court reduced cash bond to $2000 with same conditions as previously ordered.  Defendant is to notify the Clerk of Court of his mailing address if the bond is posted.
